To get an insight about the datasets and finding out if my data-sets have outliers, I used box plot to visualize the spread of day and hour datasets.¶

As we can see, for the day data-set we have:¶

  • The average rented bikes in the year 2012 is higher than year 2011.

  • The average number of rented bikes is higher during Summer and Autumn. This we can also see on the box plot for months. From May till October on average users (casual and registered) rented more bikes compared to other months.

  • On average users rent more bikes when there is no holiday.

  • On average the number of rented bikes is almost equal during different days of a week.

  • On average users rent more bikes when the weather is clear. As the weather gets worse, the average number of users also decrease.

For the hour datsset, I used the box plots to see the outliers. By looking at the box plot on hourly counts, we can see that¶

  • The average counts of rented bikes increases from 5 to 8, then it drops and stay almost the same from 9 to 15 and again increases from 16 to 17 and it drops till midnight.

  • On average the during 7-9 in the morining and 16-19 in the afternoon, users rented more bikes compared the other time of the day.

  • The max number of rented bikes is at 17 and 18.

By looking at the box plot for different seasosn and months, we can observe that¶

  • On average users rent more bikes during summer and autumn from May till October.

By looking at the box plot for hourly counts in different weather situation, we can see that¶

  • On average users rent more bikes when the weather is better.

Outliers¶

Since the hourly count of rented bikes is right skewed, I used log transformation to decrease the variation in the dataset and then remove outliers from our dataset.¶

Log transformation for the hourly counts of rented bikes¶

In [30]:
df_hour['log_cnt'] = np.log(df_hour['cnt'] +1)

Lasso Regression¶

In [42]:
alpha_list =[0.01, 0.1, 0.2, 0.4, 0.6, 0.8, 1.1, 2, 4, 6, 8, 16]

rmse_train_list_lasso = list()
rmse_test_list_lasso = list()
R2_score_test_list_lasso = list()
mad_list_train_lasso = list()
mad_list_test_lasso =list()

for alpha in alpha_list:
    reg_lasso = linear_model.Lasso(alpha)
    reg_lasso.fit(train_features, train_labels)

    train_labels_pred = reg_lasso.predict(train_features)
    test_labels_pred =  reg_lasso.predict(test_features)

    rmse_train = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(train_labels, train_labels_pred))
    rmse_train_list_lasso.append(rmse_train)
    
    rmse_test = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(test_labels, test_labels_pred))
    rmse_test_list_lasso.append(rmse_test)
    
    R2_score_test = r2_score(test_labels, test_labels_pred)
    R2_score_test_list_lasso.append(R2_score_test)
    
    mad_train_lasso = np.mean(np.absolute(train_labels_pred - np.mean(train_labels_pred)))
    mad_list_train_lasso.append(mad_train_lasso)
    
    mad_test_lasso = np.mean(np.absolute(test_labels_pred - np.mean(test_labels_pred)))
    mad_list_test_lasso.append(mad_test_lasso)

    
    print("Root Mean Squared Error for test set {} and train set {} for alpha {} \n". format(rmse_test, rmse_train, alpha))    
    print('R2 Score for our test set {} for alpha {} \n' .format(R2_score_test, alpha))
    print('Lasso Regression coefficient:\n %s \n'%reg_lasso.coef_)
    print('Mean Absolute Deviation for the train set {} and test set {} for alpha {}\n'.format(mad_train_lasso, mad_test_lasso, alpha))
    print(60*'--')

from sklearn.linear_model import Ridge

rmse_test_list_ridge = list()

mad_list_test_ridge = list()
for alpha in alpha_list:
    reg_ridge = linear_model.Ridge(alpha)
    reg_ridge.fit(train_features, train_labels)

    train_labels_pred = reg_ridge.predict(train_features)
    test_labels_pred =  reg_ridge.predict(test_features)

    rmse_train = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(train_labels, train_labels_pred))
    rmse_train_list_ridge.append(rmse_train)
    
    rmse_test= np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(test_labels, test_labels_pred))
    rmse_test_list_ridge.append(rmse_test)
    
    mad_train_ridge = np.mean(np.absolute(train_labels_pred - np.mean(train_labels_pred)))
    mad_list_train_ridge.append(mad_train_ridge)    
    
    mad_test_ridge = np.mean(np.absolute(test_labels_pred - np.mean(test_labels_pred)))
    mad_list_test_ridge.append(mad_test_ridge)

    
    R2_score_test = r2_score(test_labels, test_labels_pred)   
    R2_score_test_list_ridge.append(R2_score_test)
    
    print("Root Mean Squared Error for test set {} and train set {} for alpha {}\n". format(rmse_test, rmse_train, alpha))
    print('R2 Score for our test set for alpha {} is:  {}\n ' .format(alpha, R2_score_test))
    print('Mean Absolute Deviation for the train set {} and test set {}\n'.format(mad_train_ridge, mad_test_ridge
                                                                                 
                                                                                 ))
    print(60*'--')

from sklearn.ensemble import GradientBoostingRegressor

estimators = np.arange(30, 200, 10)
R2_score_test_list_gbr = []
rmse_train_list_gbr = []
rmse_test_list_gbr = []
mad_list_train_gbr = []
mad_list_test_gbr = []

for n in estimators:
    model = GradientBoostingRegressor(n_estimators=n, learning_rate=0.1, max_depth=1, random_state=0, loss='ls')
    model.fit(train_features, train_labels)
    
    
    test_labels_pred = model.predict(test_features)
    train_labels_pred = model.predict(train_features)
        
    rmse_train = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(train_labels, train_labels_pred))
    rmse_train_list_gbr.append(rmse_train)
    
    rmse_test= np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(test_labels, test_labels_pred))
    rmse_test_list_gbr.append(rmse_test)
    
    mad_train_gbr = np.mean(np.absolute(train_labels_pred - np.mean(train_labels_pred)))
    mad_list_train_gbr.append(mad_train_gbr)
    
    mad_test_gbr = np.mean(np.absolute(test_labels_pred - np.mean(test_labels_pred)))
    mad_list_test_gbr.append(mad_test_gbr)
    
    R2_score_test = r2_score(test_labels, test_labels_pred)   
    R2_score_test_list_gbr.append(R2_score_test)
    
    print("Root Mean Squared Error for test set {} and train set {} for {} estimators\n". format(rmse_test, rmse_train, n))
    print('R2 Score for our test set: %.6f\n' %R2_score_test)
    print('Mean Absolute Deviation for the train set {} and test set {}\n'.format(mad_train_gbr, mad_test_gbr))
    print(60*'--')
